PART 2 — WEP Cracking

This is one of the most important historical security lessons.


---

What is WEP?

WEP

(Wired Equivalent Privacy)

Early WiFi security protocol.

Goal:

Protect wireless networks.


---

Original Idea

WiFi
↓
Encryption
↓
Secure Network

Sounded good.


---

Reality

Weak implementation.

Weak cryptography.

Design flaws.


---

Result

Attackers could recover WiFi keys.


---

Why Did WEP Fail?

Not because encryption itself is bad.

Because:

Weak Key Management


---

Repeated Keys


---

Design Flaws


---

Predictable Patterns


---

Security Lesson

Your manager will LOVE this lesson.

Remember:

> Security often fails because of implementation, not because of the algorithm itself.




---

Example

Imagine:

Strong cryptography.

But:

Password = admin123

Still insecure.


---

Modern Equivalent

Organizations today may have:

Strong AES

Strong PKI

Strong Authentication


But poor:

Configuration

Key management

Access controls


Result:

Security incident.


---

Banking Application

Banks don't use WEP.

But WEP teaches an important principle:

> Technology that was once secure can become insecure over time.




---

Why Security Teams Care About Legacy Systems

Old technologies remain in production.

Examples:

Old algorithms

Old certificates

Unsupported software


These create risk.


---

Think Beyond Academics

Question:

Why wasn't WEP immediately replaced?

Answer:

Because replacing technology across large organizations is expensive and complex.

This is a very real business challenge.


