---

90-Second Summary For Your Manager

> Steganography and encryption solve different problems. Encryption hides the contents of data, while steganography hides the existence of data itself. Steganography is commonly associated with malware, covert communication, and data exfiltration. WEP is an important historical example showing that security controls can fail because of weak implementation and design decisions, even when encryption is present. The broader lesson is that security depends not only on strong algorithms but also on proper implementation, configuration, and lifecycle management.




---

Most likely question your manager may ask

> "What's the biggest lesson from WEP?"



Answer:

> The biggest lesson is that security can fail even when encryption exists. Weak implementation, poor key management, and design flaws can make a system vulnerable despite using cryptographic controls. This lesson remains relevant in modern enterprise security.
